docs.abstract: We asked the Democratic presidential candidates how they would improve the health care system. Some want to eliminate private insurance, but many others said that was a step too far.
docs.snippet: We asked the Democratic presidential candidates how they would improve the health care system. Some want to eliminate private insurance, but many others said that was a step too far.
docs.lead_paragraph: “Medicare for all” is the hottest idea in the Democratic presidential race for overhauling the nation’s health care system, and it is a phrase quite likely to be heard repeatedly at the first debates this week. But despite all the buzz, it turns out that the concept is dividing the 2020 field.

headline.main: ‘Medicare for All’ vs. ‘Public Option’: The 2020 Field Is Split, Our Survey Shows
headline.print_headline: Incremental or Seismic Changes? 2020 Candidates Are Split on Health Care

docs.lead_paragraph: SOUTH BEND, Ind. — It was more than an hour into Thursday’s Democratic debate before the community activists watching back home finally heard Mayor Pete Buttigieg face the tough questions they were waiting for.

docs.abstract: From the dawn of his mayoralty, Mr. Buttigieg has wrestled with the sort of complicated issues of race and criminal justice that afflict communities nationwide.
docs.snippet: From the dawn of his mayoralty, Mr. Buttigieg has wrestled with the sort of complicated issues of race and criminal justice that afflict communities nationwide.
docs.lead_paragraph: Thirteen weeks after taking office, Pete Buttigieg fired South Bend’s popular African-American police chief. The episode threatened his standing with some black people in South Bend, a relationship that was further strained this month when a white police officer killed a black man there.

headline.main: Pete Buttigieg and the South Bend Police

docs.abstract: In a speech in Washington, Bernie Sanders laid out his vision of “Medicare for all” and asked Democrats to join him in refusing money from health care PACs, lobbyists and executives.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senator Bernie Sanders of Vermont, seeking to bring fresh momentum to his presidential campaign, offered a vigorous defense on Wednesday of his signature issue, “Medicare for all,” and called for all Democratic candidates to pledge to reject contributions from the health care industry.

headline.main: Sanders Calls for Rivals to Reject Money From Health Care Industry

docs.abstract: After the president sided with Kim Jong-un’s government in mocking Mr. Biden’s intelligence, Mr. Biden let an aide rebut it instead of taking on Mr. Trump himself.
docs.snippet: After the president sided with Kim Jong-un’s government in mocking Mr. Biden’s intelligence, Mr. Biden let an aide rebut it instead of taking on Mr. Trump himself.
docs.lead_paragraph: HOUSTON — President Trump sided again on Tuesday with the government of North Korean leader Kim Jong-un in mocking Joseph R. Biden Jr.’s intelligence, an extraordinary alignment of a United States president and an authoritarian regime against an American politician — and an insult that Mr. Biden pooh-poohed by letting an aide rebut it.

headline.main: Trump and Biden Campaign Trade Jabs Over North Korea’s Remarks
headline.print_headline: Biden, Saying He Won’t Engage in ‘Mud Wrestling,’ Brushes Off President’s Latest Insults
